Text.Value: It was strategy - not personal.
We must remain vigilant. And grateful. I will join your camp tonight. There, we will discuss the spirals of time - past and future. And we will make merry in the present, wherein we reside.
You have defeated Ketheric Thorm, yet you who were content to leave Dame Aylin in his thrall until it served you best. How do you account for it?

EditorData.logicalname: Did not save NS in SHA; Isobel died in HAV

Text.Value: See you there.
Failure is disquieting. But you are lucky - for you have failed at a destiny that was not yours to fulfil.
Good. I'll see you there.
True, we live at the mercy of the gods. But we get to choose to whom we yoke our fate.
No need to wait. I freed you so I could kill Ketheric, but I have no interest in an alliance.
We must remain vigilant. And grateful. I will join your camp tonight. There, we will discuss the Moonmaiden's plan for you - for your past, your future.
Isobel is dead. But you live - you who were content to leave me in the thrall of foul Ketheric Thorm.

EditorData.logicalname: Did not save NS in SHA; Isobel died in COL

Text.Value: It takes a lion's heart to admit such a terrible mistake. I will forgive you, in time.
Blessings of the Moonmaiden upon all beneath her watchful eye.
Fine. I'll see you this evening.
I don't think so. Our journey together ends here.
I will visit your camp later. Perhaps the madness of battle will have left you, and you will be ready to speak sense.
We live at the mercy of the gods. Even I, immortal, have no guarantee of days to come.
I'd do it again, if the whim struck me.
And you - Sharran. Cleric of the Lady of Loss, who is so much more than she appears. You and Dame Aylin have dangerous ground to tread.
Good. Whatever you think you know about me had better be worth it. You've already cost me dearly.

EditorData.NodeContext: Trying to mask anxiety with a tough exterior.

Text.Value: Aye, it was. It was a failure I won't soon forget. Still, you are no lost cause, are you?
I may not live long - Lady Shar wanted me to kill you. Now I've failed her, and spited you.
If you seek to protect it, our aims are aligned - even if you've much to learn about the methods of a true champion.
They will keep. Let us first retire to a more restful place. Your camp will do.
Be careful, little soldier. Whims are not all that can strike.

EditorData.NodeContext: Voice lowered, threatening. The player was a prick to her and now she's feeling the full force of her hatred.

Text.Value: I apologise. It was wrong of me to leave you in Ketheric's clutches.
You would deny Dame Aylin, daughter of the Moonmaiden, paladin of the selfsame Selûne?
I would.
I will not forget it. But nor will I turn down a powerful ally in the fight for Faerûn.
We will cover some small part of it soon.
Ketheric is dead. Balthazar is dead. Isobel, sweet Isobel, is no more. But we, we live.

EditorData.logicalname: Saved NS in SHA; Isobel died in COL

Text.Value: I will join your camp tonight. There is much you should know. About the Moonmaiden, about your past. Your future.
Why delay? Just tell me now.
What do you mean by that?
Reject the moon, if it be your will. It will not stop her from lending you her light. Good day.
I will join your camp, that we may discuss what must needs be discussed.
You certainly will.
All in its own time, the Sharran-who-wasn't.
I have questions now.
Not personal for you, perhaps. You played a game of life and death, using mine as a chip in your pile.
I am Dame Aylin. Daughter of the Moonmaiden, Selûne; champion of her causes in this fine realm.

Synopsis: The player has a chance to catch up with Nightsong if she survived Act 2, and Isobel is dead
